Isabelle Coetzee, News24The pig snout that was left on the gate of a mosque in Simon's Town, Cape Town. (Facebook) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - The desecration of two Cape Town mosques is an assault on the country&rsquo;s democracy, the FW de Klerk Foundation said on Wednesday. It believed that most South Africans disagreed with what the vandals had done and that most citizens respected religious freedom.&nbsp;The organisation referred to Chapter 2 of the Bill of Rights, which states: "Everyone has the right to freedom of conscience, religion, thought, belief, and opinion.&nbsp;"The foundation stands with the vast majority in expressing outrage at the attack on places of worship and reverence," it said in a statement. &nbsp;&nbsp;Blood was found spattered on the walls and pulpit of Masjidul Jamiah in Kalk Bay on Monday morning. The vandals damaged property inside the building. The mosque is a heritage site and was founded in 1898. It was renovated last year.A mosque in Simon&rsquo;s Town was also desecrated on Saturday. A pig snout and blood were left on the doorstep. Pigs are forbidden in Islam.A few days earlier, Langebaan resident, Liam Ferreira, wrote a Facebook post ranting about the Muslim call to prayer, which takes place five times a day.&nbsp;He later apologised and then joined the chorus of condemnation following the desecration of the Simon&rsquo;s Town mosque.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.